					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Hard Times at the University of New Mexico Press</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 4-15-09</p>
			
			
							<p>I once had a gig writing press releases for a Denver concert promoter.&nbsp; As the author of &#8220;John Tesh To Grace Red Rocks With His Magnetic Music,&#8221; I can attest that the press release is one of the least interesting genres to write and to read.&nbsp; It was to my great surprise, then, when I recently received a press release from the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.unmpress.com/" title="University of New Mexico Press">University of New Mexico Press</a> that was filled with suspense, drama, intrigue, and actual news.
</p>
<p>
The word from Albuquerque was this: 
</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;Despite months of budget-cutting and assurances from upper management that jobs were not in jeopardy, employees of UNM Press were left stunned yesterday by announcements of layoffs and possible outsourcing of their jobs.
</p>
<p>
Two employees, Glenda Madden, marketing and sales manager for the press for seven years and a thirty-three-year university press publishing veteran, and Lisa Pacheco, a junior acquisitions editor, were told April 30 would be their last day at the press. The press&#8217;s publicity department was also told to cut one job from its two-person staff, the result of which is pending&#8230;
</p>
<p>
Press publicist Amanda Sutton, an eight-year publishing professional who has been with the press for five years, was called by Richard Schuetz to a meeting with Luther Wilson, press director, mid-morning on Monday. Mr. Wilson, after citing the recession and the press&#8217;s operating deficit, asked Ms. Sutton to decide whether she would remain on staff or whether her assistant of three years, Katherine MacGilvray, would be let go.
</p>
<p>
&#8216;I have a difficult time determining the fate of a fellow colleague, to whom I owe much loyalty and respect. Sacrificing up a colleague is not part of my job description,&#8217; says Ms. Sutton.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://chronicle.com/news/article/6232/employees-revolt-over-layoffs-at-the-u-of-new-mexico-press" title="The Chronicle of Higher Education">The Chronicle of Higher Education</a> followed up with Wynn Goering, the University of New Mexico&#8217;s vice provost for academic affairs:
</p>
<p>
&#8220;&#8216;UNM Press has been hard hit by the recession,&#8217; [Goering] said, with a projected operating deficit of $690,000 by June 30. &#8216;Given the magnitude of the problems, we simply didn&#8217;t see any way forward without restructuring the business model and reducing its work force.&#8217; (Via <a target="_blank" href="http://news.shelf-awareness.com/msgget.jsp?mid=2777823" title="Shelf Awareness">Shelf Awareness</a>)
</p>
<p>
Do you hear that?&nbsp; That&#8217;s the sound of me shaking my fist at this darn recession.&nbsp; If only my fist were mightier.&nbsp; The University of New Mexico Press publishes a lot of <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/otero_mesa_captures_the_rugged_beauty_of_the_new_mexico_grassland/C39/L39/" title="great">great</a> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/colorado_abstract_showcases_states_contemporary_artists/C39/L39/" title="books">books</a>, and I sure hope they sort all this out.
</p>
<p>
While I&#8217;m at it, why don&#8217;t I dish up some even more disturbing news. The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.bendweekly.com/Statewide-News/17287.html" title="Bend Weekly">Bend Weekly</a> reported:
</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;A published children&#8217;s author from Portland has been charged with a variety of child pornography offenses. Kevin Patrick Bath, 50, who writes under the name K.P. Bath, was arraigned Monday afternoon in U.S. District Court on an indictment charging him with one count each of distributing, transferring, and receiving child pornography, and two counts of possessing child pornography. He entered pleas of not guilty to each count. Trial is set for June 9, 2009, before U.S. District Judge Ancer L. Haggerty.&#8221; (Via <a target="_blank" href="http://www.publishersmarketplace.com/" title="Publishers Lunch">Publishers Lunch</a>)</p></blockquote>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/publisher_says_it_wont_print_b.html" title="The Oregonian">The Oregonian</a> reported that Bath&#8217;s publisher, Little, Brown Books for Young Readers, has decided not to publish his next book. (Duh.)
</p>
<p>
On a brighter note, the annual <a target="_blank" href="http://eventful.com/denver/events/denver-public-library-2009-evil-companions-literary-/E0-001-020343205-4" title="Evil Companions Literary Award">Evil Companions Literary Award</a>, sponsored by the Tattered Cover and the Denver Public Library, will honor Timothy Egan this year, for his award-winning book <I>The Worst Hard Time</I>&#8230;about the Great Depression.&nbsp; (The party is at The Oxford Hotel on April 16, 6 p.m., and tickets are $65-$150, with a &#8220;Hard Times&#8221; ticket rate of $50 for students and educators.)
</p>
<p>
Isn&#8217;t there anything good that&#8217;s happened lately?&nbsp; Well, maybe one thing.&nbsp; The folks at the <a target="_blank" href="http://wyomingarts.blogspot.com/2009/03/brad-watson-in-new-yorker.html" title="Wyoming Arts Blog">Wyoming Arts Blog</a> pointed out that Brad Watson had a story published in The New Yorker.&nbsp; <a target="_blank" href="http://wiki.wyomingauthors.org/Brad+Watson" title="Brad Watson">Brad Watson</a> is a writing professor at the University of Wyoming, and his story &#8221;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.newyorker.com/fiction/features/2009/04/06/090406fi_fiction_watson" title="Visitation">Visitation</a>&#8221; appeared in the April 6 issue.&nbsp; It doesn&#8217;t get much better than that.&nbsp; 
</p>
<p>
The story itself is the sad and poignant tale of a man who travels to San Diego to visit his young son, who is in the custody of his estranged wife.&nbsp; It begins: &#8220;Loomis had never believed that line about the quality of despair being that it was unaware of being despair. He&#8217;d been painfully aware of his own despair for most of his life.&#8221;  I suppose this sends a useful message: when times are tough, go and make art out of your misery.
</p>
<p>
And if you&#8217;re looking for something to do to cheer yourself up on tax day, check out <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_steven_rinella/C39/L39/" title="Steven Rinella">Steven Rinella</a>&#8216;s talk on Wednesday, April 15 at the Fort Collins Hilton Hotel for for CSU&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://lib.colostate.edu/about/news/2009/wotp/" title="Writers On The Plains">Writers On The Plains</a> Series.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional book news or events to share, preferably of the non-depressing variety?&nbsp; Please <script type="text/javascript">
