		</div>

		<!-- Begin Comments -->
		
		<b>Comment By Bill Croke, 4-15-09</b>
		<p>Jenny, If the university presses are in trouble (and I'm sure UNM isn't alone) it's mainly because academically-oriented books don't sell. Academics read academics, but there is no widely dispersed audience. Said presses are usually a reflection of the institutions themselves, and are captive of the prevailing multicultural pathologies found on campus. They can blame the recession all they want. And I think the big New York houses are seeing the same thing. If you publish garbage, it's garbage. Everybody "writes" today, from alienated academics who hate their jobs, to Paris Hilton, who is a brand. 99% of  books published annually in America aren't worth reading, they're merely an extension of the pop culture. Remember Pamela Anderson pushing a book somebody ghosted for her on Letterman, and she didn't know who Ernest Hemingway was. That's a perfect metaphor for our Republic of Letters. Oddly enough, conservative houses like Regnery are doing well: Ann Coulter, Mark Levin, et al. But they don't get reviewed in the liberal media, such as the New York Times. Bottom line: University Presses, RIP. But who reads them?</p>
		
		<b>Comment By rkrugg, 4-15-09</b>
		<p>"I can attest that the press release is one of the least interesting genres to write and to read."<br />
<br />
Sorry, gotta say that, if you're doing it right, this just isn't the case...</p>
		
		<b>Comment By mbartley, 4-16-09</b>
		<p>Who reads them Bill? I do. I am a voracious reader of fiction and non-fiction. The American West is my particular obsession but I try and remain open to a broad range of reading. I could not disagree with you more fully. The University presses publish some of the finer works I have ever encountered. In our region alone we have a number of fine U publishers including two of exceptional merit, the presses of Nebraska and Oklahoma. The loss of these "alternative" publishers would be a bitter blow to our culture. Our stories are who we are. We need more not less.<br />
Also, Jenny, I was able to attend Steve Rinella's talk here in the Fort. He is a young writer with talent to burn and a man comfortable with complexity and careful in his assertions. What a joy to listen to someone who does not settle for the easy answer while doling out pablum. He spoke on a subject I know a bit about and I was impressed with his thoughtful articulate views on buffalo, people, and the land.<br />
Michael</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Bill Croke, 4-19-09</b>
		<p>M.Bartley,  The loss of the "alternative"  university presses would be a "bitter blow to our culture" if they were indeed the least bit heterodox. But they're not. They are merely our own regional reflection of the whole of contemporary American "culture", which is elitist, politically correct, and "progressive". Not only that, they put out most of the bad writing found at your local Barnes and Noble. Much of what Jenny reviews --almost daily, she is prolific--reflects this. The university presses mostly put out books reflecting the "struggles" of "oppressed" folks: Native Americans, Hispanics, and western women kept down by the patriarchy, etc. Patty Limerick, Mary Clearman Blew, Kim Barnes,John Clayton, Judy Blunt. I've always thought William Kittredge was a regional "academic hack" in the Gore Vidal sense. Terry Tempest Williams and Gretel Ehrlich, though they have national audiences. Same with Rick Bass, which reminds me that much contemporary western literature is green-driven; it's always a flaw in a writer's artistic integrity to let a political agenda drive their art, so to speak. I would think MFA programs across the West are loaded with Bass imitators. Thomas McGuane has been writing the same novel over and over for thirty years. Larry McMurtry lives in Texas, which is the South, not the West. He co-authors real horse operas now. Cormac McCarthy had integrity and then discovered Oprah's Book Club. Edward Abbey and Tony Hillerman are dead (RIP). That's about it. A few random thoughts. Bottom line, Bartley: it's mostly a wasteland out there. Try Tolstoy and the rest of the dead white guys.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 4-20-09</b>
		<p>Wow, Bill.  I feel like I should respond, but I'm not sure how with all that you said!  I enjoy the work of a lot of the writers you named, and I'm not sure what your point is about university presses, because several of them publish with major publishers--Kim Barnes, Judy Blunt, Terry Tempest Williams, and Rick Bass.<br />
<br />
I thought Mary Clearman Blew's novel "Jackalope Dreams" was a great book, and a good example of the kind of work published by a university press (in this case, my favorite one, the University of Nebraska Press) that otherwise might fall through the cracks.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.newwest.net%2Ftopic%2Farticle%2Fold_and_new_montana_clash_in_accomplished_jackalope_dreams%2FC39%2FL39%2F">http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/old_and_new_montana_clash_in_accomplished_jackalope_dreams/C39/L39/</a><br />
<br />
I agree that Tolstoy is wonderful, Bill, but the question is, who else do you like to read?  Anybody alive?<br />
<br />
(Not that there's anything wrong with your reading preferences.  I have a friend that will only read coming-of-age novels about males in contemporary America.  At least he reads!)</p>
		
		<b>Comment By mbartley, 4-20-09</b>
		<p>Bill, a green driven wasteland is what you see when you survey the literary west. I don't. Nothing much more to say about it. When two people disagree to the core, it is hard to know where to go with the discussion. Let me try. I've read the dead Russians. Should I stop reading now? Everything else is just drivel? Also, could you explain to me how the Russians managed to maintain their artistic integrity in the face of their own political agendas? I read a lot of white guys, Stegner and Harrison to name just two not yet in our discussion. I also read a lot of work by folks of deeper shades of color some of whom, and I know this is shocking, come without a penis. Folks such as Welch, Baca, Erdrich and Proulx, again just to name a few, are among my favorites. Perhaps, we can agree that nearly all writers have some sort of political point of view or agenda. Certainly, we can agree that we prefer writers and stories that share or confirm our world view. Maybe, we can take the next step and try and read works that may shatter our preconceived notions about ourselves and our world. Slumped against an old busted cottonwood staring at the page in wonderment at notions beyond my own precious meanderings is my idea of a fine way to whittle away an evening. I like Turgenev but, tonight I think I'll finish Louise Erdrich's novel The Last Report on the Miracles at Little No Horse. So far I've encountered an old priest with a womans plumbing. Well, this should be interesting. I hope it's not a wasteland.<br />
Michael</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Bill Croke, 4-20-09</b>
		<p>Jenny, Sorry, I'm just a curmudgeon. I'm rereading more and more old friends from the classics. The new administration has got me on what you might call a political cautionary tale kick lately. Orwell's "1984" and just last night the first 35 pages of "Animal Farm". A couple of weeks ago Arthur Koestler's "Darkness at Noon", returning to it after 20 years. The best novel ever as a meditation on the totalitarian mind. I also like staight history and this past winter read Walter Isaacson's biography of Ben Franklin. Also a dusty old thing found at the public library: Thomas Costain's "The White and the Gold", a history of New France. The older I get I just want to be fascinated and amused.I've long ago got over the notion that I need to read a particular book because everybody else is.  I write about the West (journalism, reviews, etc. in the conservative press,though as you know reviewing is dying everywhere, for money anyway) and I've reviewed many of those writers I've mentioned in the previous post. The literature of the contemporary West takes itself too seriously. It comes with the territory. But most writers in, say, Montana (to name a state whose literati have pretensions as big as the,well, Big Sky), are no better than most writers in Indiana or Pennsylvania. They just have a nicer view from the front porch. Oh, and if most of the writers I named are not with university presses but New York publishers, well, good for them, but that future isn't bright either.</p>
		
